Column Comment.0: INTEREST SET IDENTIFIER: unique identifier for the interest set.
Column Comment.1: BA INTEREST SET SEQUENCE NUMBER: unique sequencing component to allowverioning of the interest set over time.
Column Comment.2: PARTNER BUSINESS ASSOCIATE ID: the business associate who is a parter.
Column Comment.3: PARTNER OBSERVATION NUMBER: This column is used when a businessassociate holds more than one interest share of a specific interest type (working,production etc) in a partnership. This can happen as a result of corporate mergers orasset acquisitions. If a partner only holds one interest share, this number will alwaysbe 1. Please note that this column should not be used to track multiple interest types;in this event, a new interest set must be created.
Column Comment.4: BUSINESS ASSOCIATE: Unique identifier for a business associate, such as aperson, company, regulatory agency, government or consortium.
Column Comment.5: CONTACT OBSERVATION NUMBER: a unique number for the occurence of thecontact for the interest set.
Column Comment.6: CONTACT_ID: The unique BA ID for the contact for the interest set.
Column Comment.7: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this row of data is currently eitheractive / valid (Y) or inactive / invalid (N).
Column Comment.8: ADDRESS OBSERVATION NUMBER: A number used to uniquely identifying anaddress for a Business Associate.
Column Comment.9: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.10: CONTACT ORG BA ID: Unique identifer for the contact business associate.
Column Comment.11: ORGANIZATION SEQUENCE NUMBER: a unique number added to alloworganizations to be versioned over time.
Column Comment.12: BUSINESS ASSOCIATE ORGANIZATION IDENTIFIER: unique identifier for anorganization of a company or organization
Column Comment.13: BA INTEREST SET PARTNER CONTACT ROLE: the role played by the contact forthe partner in the interest set, such as negotiator, authorization, legal representativeetc.
Column Comment.14: CONTRACT ID: Unique identifier for the contract table.
Column Comment.15: EFFECTIVE DATE: the date on which this row of data first came into effect from abusiness perspective.
Column Comment.16: EXPIRY DATE: the date on which this row of data is no longer in effect from abusiness perspective.
Column Comment.17: INACTIVE DATE: the date when the contact actually was no longer assigned to be acontact for the interest set.
Column Comment.18: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should becreated.
Column Comment.19: PROVISION ID: unique identifier for a contract provision
Column Comment.20: REMARK: Narrative remarks about this row of data.
Column Comment.21: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.22: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.23: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.24: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.25: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.26: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.27: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.28: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
